<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>Recall 03513 - Steering Columns of RE (Rear Engine) and FE (Front Engine) Busses Built Between 10/28/1993
        and 5/21/2003
    </stitle>
    <recall id="rec03513">
        <recallnumber>03513</recallnumber>
        <market>U.S., Export</market>
        <recalldate>November, 2003</recalldate>
        <subjectfile>STEERING</subjectfile>
        <subject>Steering Columns of RE (Rear Engine) and FE (Front Engine) Busses Built Between 10/28/1993 and
            5/21/2003
        </subject>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>3000 RE
                    <daterange>
                        <startdate>10/28/1993</startdate>
                        <enddate>05/21/2003</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>3000 FE
                    <daterange>
                        <startdate>10/28/1993</startdate>
                        <enddate>05/21/2003</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
                <ucodegroup/>

                <ucode>05708</ucode>
                <ucode>05710</ucode>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <defect>
            <para>
                <exhotlnk document="../recalls/Rec03513.pdf" bookname="RECALL">Print ready (PDF file) copy of the dealer
                    letter
                </exhotlnk>
            </para>
            <para>
                <exhotlnk document="../recalls/Cus03513.pdf" bookname="RECALL">Print ready (PDF file) copy of the
                    customer letter
                </exhotlnk>
            </para>
            <para>A steering shaft yoke pinch bolt, located below the steering column, can catch on the rubber steering
                boot. If this pinch bolt catches on the steering boot, a sudden resistance in steering movement could
                occur which may cause a
                <emph type="bold">vehicle crash without warning, possibly</emph>
                resulting in
                <emph type="bold">property damage, personal injury, or death</emph>.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>MODELS INVOLVED</title>
            </para>
            <para>This campaign includes RE and FE busses built 10/28/1993 through 5/21/2003 with tilt or tilt/telescope
                steering columns (Feature Codes: 05708 or 05710) at the Conway, Arkansas bus plant.
            </para>
        </defect>
        <ownernote>
            <para>International Truck and Engine Corporation will notify owners of these vehicles about this campaign.
                During the recall process a listing of owner names and addresses will be furnished to the involved
                dealers to enable dealers to follow up with owners and have the vehicles corrected. You must limit the
                use of this listing to this campaign, because the list may contain information obtained from state motor
                vehicle registration records and the use of such motor vehicle registration data for purposes other than
                this campaign is a violation of law in several states.
            </para>
        </ownernote>
        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="18">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent serious eye injury, always wear safe eye protection when you perform vehicle
                        maintenance or service.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Block the wheels to prevent the vehicle from moving.</para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <title>Steering Column Removal</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect steering column wiring.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351301" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351301.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove steering column mounting bracket lower bolts, one on each side of the steering
                    column (Figure 2).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351302" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351302.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Be sure to note which bolt holds the column harness P-Clip in place (Figure 3).</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">This bolt may be longer than the other steering column mounting bolts. If it
                            is installed in any other hole, it may restrict the steering column's ability to turn
                            freely.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351303" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351303.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>TO AVOID STEERING COLUMN DAMAGE AND RESTRICTION OF STEERING SHAFT MOVEMENT, REPLACE HARNESS
                        P-CLIP AND BOLT BACK INTO SAME HOLE.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove steering column mounting bracket
                    <emph type="bold">upper right-hand</emph>
                    bolt
                    <emph type="bold">ONLY</emph>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351304" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351304.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove
                    <emph type="bold">right-hand</emph>
                    steering column bracket nuts. Remove
                    <emph type="bold">right- hand</emph>
                    bracket from column and cowl.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>STEERING COLUMN IS NOW ONLY SUPPORTED BY LEFT-HAND UPPER BOLT.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0351305" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351305.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reposition steering column boot downward for easier access to column shaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351306" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351306.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 6</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mark both halves of the steering column to keep shaft in place during reinstallation.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351307" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351307.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove steering column mounting bracket
                    <emph type="bold">upper left-hand</emph>
                    bolt.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351308" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351308.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove steering column by sliding shaft from slip yoke. Place on bench.</para>
            </step1>
            <para>
                <title>Steering Boot Inspection (Removal/Replacement)</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect steering boot for holes.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">See Figure 9 and 10 for representations and possible locations of a hole.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351309" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351309.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0351310" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351310.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="232px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 10</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">If a hole is found, continue on to step 12. If no hole is found, skip to step
                        14.
                    </emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove steering boot from floor.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new steering boot to floor.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">FE Busses have an oval shaped boot while RE Busses have a round shaped boot. Both
                        are installed in a similar manner.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351311" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351311.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="472px"
                         scalefitheight="392px"/>
                <caption>Figure 11 (FE Bus Shown)</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <title>Heat Shrink Band Clamp Installation</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove heat shrink band clamp from cardboard carrier.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Slide clamp over U-joint yoke.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position clamp
                    <emph type="bold">centered</emph>
                    on the pinch bolt threads.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid burns and hand injuries, wear heat resistant gloves to help hold the shrink band in
                        place during contraction.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a heat gun, apply heat to band clamp until it contracts into place. See Figure 12,
                    13, and 14.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351312" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351312.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 12</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0351313" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351313.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 13</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0351314" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351314.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 14</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <title>Steering Column Installation</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install steering column assembly into lower column slip yoke. Be sure to align paint
                    marks.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351315" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351315.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 15</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install steering column mounting bracket
                    <emph type="bold">upper left-hand</emph>
                    bolt.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351316" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351316.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 16</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position steering boot as shown.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">Line up holes</emph>
                        in boot with lower steering column mounting bracket holes. Rubber boot should be positioned
                        <emph type="bold">under</emph>
                        lower column plastic cover.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0351317" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351317.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 17</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0351318" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0351318.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 18</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install remaining steering column fasteners. Torque all bolts to
                    <emph type="bold">17-23 LbF-Ft</emph>
                    (23-31 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>TO AVOID STEERING COLUMN DAMAGE AND RESTRICTION OF STEERING SHAFT MOVEMENT, INSTALL HARNESS
                        P-CLIP AND BOLT BACK INTO SAME HOLE.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Re-connect steering column electrical harness.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start vehicle. Spin steering wheel to ensure there is no drag on shaft due to the P-Clip
                    bolt being in the wrong hole.
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If resistance is felt, find and place longest bolt in hole where harness P-clip is
                        located.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If
                        <emph type="bold">no</emph>
                        resistance is felt, the Service Procedure is complete.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
